      "content": "Great question! The shape of the wing, or airfoil, is designed to guide the air to move faster over the top surface naturally. As air approaches the wing, it's forced to travel along the curved surface. The curvature of the top surface effectively 'squeezes' the air into a thinner path, which, according to the conservation of mass, means it must move faster to fill the space. This is similar to how a river narrows and speeds up when it flows through a constricted channel. So, the wing's shape doesn't just force the air to move faster; it channels the air into a path that requires higher velocity to maintain the same flow rate, thus creating the pressure difference that leads to lift.",
